    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-04-24T06:30:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-04-24T06:30:00-05:00" n="927"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d927">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">460.979/4–2452: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in Ceylon</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_GBA1"
                        type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Gufler</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">confidential</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Colombo</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-04-24T17:00:00+05:30"
                            >April 24, 1952—5 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>597. <persName corresp="#p_EJ2">Exter</persName>, Gov Central Bank called
                    personally today to discuss status rubber negots in light info included <gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 383 [<hi rend="italic">393</hi>], April
                        18,<note n="1" xml:id="d927fn1">Department telegram 393 to Colombo, not
                        printed, stated that although the Department was sympathetic with the
                        government’s difficulties, it would be unable to hold open the current offer
                        beyond Apr. 30 because of rapidly diminishing funds and the approaching
                        cessation of new rubber activities by <gloss target="#t_GSA1">GSA</gloss>
                        (846E.2395/4–1052).</note> given him by me. Said he pressing <gloss
                        target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> to continue talks before new govt formed as
                    contract wld bring badly needed dollars. Also believes US shld be interested in
                    order stop further shipments rubber to China. Reported new <gloss
                        target="#t_PriMin1">PriMin</gloss> desires agreement but he and <gloss
                        target="#t_PermSec1">Perm Secy</gloss>
                    <gloss target="#t_MEA1">MEA</gloss> cannot take final decision without Cabinet
                    approval which cannot be given until after elections.</p>
                <p>
                    <persName corresp="#p_EJ2">Exter</persName> has impression <gloss
                        target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> disturbed by Apr 30 deadline and inquired as to
                    reasons therefor. Gave him substance <gloss target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss>
                    383 [<hi rend="italic">393</hi>], Apr 18, but he unable understand meaning
                    “approaching cessation new rubber activities <gloss target="#t_GSA1"
                    >GSA</gloss>” unless refers to decontrol announced Apr 20 or possibility <gloss
                        target="#t_GSA1">GSA</gloss> unable make contract after end fiscal year.
                        <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> wld also appreciate clarification.<note
                        n="2" xml:id="d927fn2">Department telegram 405, Apr. 28, 1952, explained
                        that the approaching cessation of new rubber activities referred to the
                        termination on June 30 of <gloss target="#t_GSA1">GSA</gloss> purchases for
                        industry and to the fact that the U.S. rubber stockpile was nearing
                        completion (460.979/4–2452).</note>
                </p>
                <p>Finally <persName corresp="#p_EJ2">Exter</persName> inquired if it worthwhile for
                        <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> to reply to US counterproposals (<gloss
                        target="#t_Deptel1">Deptel</gloss> 376, Apr 5)<note n="3" xml:id="d927fn3">
                        <hi rend="italic">Ante</hi>, <ref target="#pg_1517">p. 1517</ref>.</note>
                    despite fact it unable sign contract before June or whether negots that basic
                    definitely closed as of Apr 30. <gloss target="#t_Emb1">Emb</gloss> answered it
                    wld transmit this question to <gloss target="#t_Dept1">Dept</gloss>.</p>
                <pb facs="0470" n="1520" xml:id="pg_1520"/>
                <p>He also informally intimated <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> cannot accept
                    price for thick pale crepes based on Singapore average for thin pale crepes and
                    questions whether Ceylon production No. 1 X, 1, and 2 former item can meet US
                    demand. Central Bank sees little difficulty in agreeing price and volume of
                    sheet.</p>
                <p>If <persName corresp="#p_EJ2">Exter</persName>’s impressions correct it appears
                        <gloss target="#t_GOC1">GOC</gloss> remains sincerely interested in contract
                    and might wish continue negots during interim before new Parl meets. It cannot
                    under any circumstances sign contract before June.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_GBA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Gufler</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
